Put a large #saucepan{} of water on to boil on medium-high heat with half the
@chicken stock powder{1/2%stock pot}. Bash the @lemongrass{1} with a #rolling
pin{} or #frying pan{} and cut it in half. Add one half to the stock. Once
the stock is boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g}. Cook at a rapid boil until
soft, ~{30%minutes}.

> TIP: Add more water if it all evaporates.

Meanwhile, remove the top and bottom from the @leek{1}, cut in half lengthways
and slice into thin half moons. Cut each @closed cup mushrooms{225%g} into four
or five slices. Cut the remaining lemongrass in half lengthways and then slice
thinly.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a frying pan on medium-high heat. Once the
oil is hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{260%g}. Cook until browned, stirring
occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the leek and mushrooms to the #pan{}. Stir
together and cook until the leek is soft and the mushrooms are brown,
~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the @ginger puree{1/2%tsp}, @easy garlic{1/2%clove}(minced) and sliced
lemongrass to your frying pan along with the @Thai style spice mix{1}. Stir
together and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @kaffir lime
leaf{1}, remaining stock pot and the @water{50%ml}. Bring to a simmer and
leave to bubble away to let the flavours develop, ~{5-7%minutes}.

> This is your curry!

> TIP: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

While the curry cooks, roughly chop the @coriander{10}%sprigs} (stalks and all).
Once the curry is ready, squeeze in half the @lime{1}, taste and then add some
salt and @ground black pepper{} if necessary. Stir in half the coriander.

When the rice is cooked, drain through a #sieve{} and discard the lemongrass.
Spoon into deep #bowls{} and ladle the chicken curry on top. Sprinkle over the
remaining coriander. Enjoy!